{"title":"Equatorial Guinea facts of the day","link":"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/871854734/0/marginalrevolution~Equatorial-Guinea-facts-of-the-day.html","date":1708512218000,"content":"<blockquote><p>After the discovery of oil in the mid-1990s, per capita income soared and catapulted the country into the club of high income countries (it peaked at over $35,000). Meanwhile, living standards stagnated at deplorable levels — from education attainment, to infant mortality rates, to poverty rates, and more. Primary school enrollment <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SE.PRM.ENRR?locations=GQ\">has declined since peaking in the early 2000s</a>. Life expectancy is 15 years lower than in countries of comparable per capita income (presently at round $7500). Poverty rates exceed 70%.</p>\r\n<p>To compound matters, the country’s oil output is in decline. Current oil production (around 52k barrels per day) is a mere 13% of peak production in the mid 2000s. As a result of decades-long neglect of the non-oil sector, overall economic output is declining in tandem with declining oil production.</p></blockquote>\r\n<p>Here is <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://kenopalo.substack.com/p/what-next-for-equatorial-guinea-after?utm_source=post-email-title&amp;publication_id=1252832&amp;post_id=141526637&amp;utm_campaign=email-post-title&amp;isFreemail=false&amp;r=3o9&amp;utm_medium=email\" target=\"_blank\">more from Ken Opalo</a>, the piece is instructive throughout.</p>\r\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2024/02/equatorial-guinea-facts-of-the-day.html\">Equatorial Guinea facts of the day</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com\">Marginal REVOLUTION</a>.</p>\r\n<img height=\"1\" width=\"1\" src=\"https://feed